<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Releases Report on Emissions; Measures to Conserve Energy Under Way</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Stacey Radnor and Christine Dellert
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 27, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1009/en_US/biodieselcrop.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: UCF News file</p>
			
			<p>Diesel fuel has been replaced with biodiesel fuel in UCF&#146;s fleet vehicles. Biodiesel fuel reduces carbon-dioxide emissions by 20 percent compared to diesel fuel.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400412e120743011469b630a7007058">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:sradnor@mail.ucf.edu">Stacey Radnor</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-4039</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.energy.ucf.edu">Center for Energy and Sustainability</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>In an effort to track its carbon footprint and lower future emissions, the University of Central Florida has released its first Greenhouse Gas Report. </p><p>Electrical consumption accounted for the most campus carbon-dioxide emissions last year, university officials found from the five sources measured  electric, natural gas, student shuttles, staff and faculty travel and campus fleet fuel. </p><p>Created by team members from UCFs Center for Energy and Sustainability, the report also focuses on going green, conserving energy and natural resources and creating a more sustainable environment for faculty, staff, alumni, students and the community.</p><p>This is a key first step in UCF meeting the American College &amp; University Presidents Climate Commitment, which we have signed as a part of the Leadership Circle, said UCF Energy Manager David Norvell. We have to know what our baseline is so that we know that progress is being made. </p><p>Many scientists believe that carbon dioxide is one of the main emissions causing temperatures to rise, potentially leading to irreversible climate shifts. </p><p>Though this is the first calculation of UCFs carbon footprint - the effect human activities have on greenhouse gases produced - future annual reports will be issued each spring. </p><p>By 2011, UCF wants to reduce its energy consumption up to 20 percent in all education and general buildings on campus. </p><p>To decrease the universitys environmental impact, many innovative measures are under way:</p><p>-- An in-house Building Commissioning team is in the process of checking campus buildings ventilation, heating and air-conditioning systems for efficient energy use. Inspections in Colburn Hall and the Classroom I building were recently completed. </p><p>-- UCF has begun to replace nearly 4,000 light bulbs in the Library with super-efficient bulbs. Lighting sensors and controls will be added to turn off lights during the day.<br /> <br />-- Diesel fuel has been replaced with biodiesel fuel in UCFs fleet vehicles. Biodiesel fuel reduces carbon-dioxide emissions by 20 percent compared to diesel fuel.</p><p>-- UCF has committed to a minimum Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) silver standard for all new buildings and major renovations. </p><p>-- The Center for Energy and Sustainability has almost completed its plug-in hybrid Toyota Prius, which uses an electric, battery-charged motor for on-campus trips. </p><p>-- Solar energy is coming to UCF for the first time. It will be used to provide hot water for the Tower I residence hall on the campus north side, and it eventually will be used in other residence halls. </p><p>-- Recycling efforts have been increased around campus to create a greener school. </p><p>-- UCF President John Hitt joined the leadership circle of the American College &amp; University Presidents Climate Commitment in February. Hitt and other college presidents from throughout the country committed to reducing campus emissions of greenhouse gases.</p><p>The Center for Energy and Sustainability aims to give students, staff and faculty the knowledge they need to become better stewards of the environment.</p><p>To see UCFs Greenhouse Gas Report, visit <a href="http://www.energy.ucf.edu/">www.energy.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
